{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17516607","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17516607"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T13:44:30+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T13:44:30+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12665"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"12665","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/12665"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.54,0.03,0.03,0.14,0.26]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"5141"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"105835"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"5141","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/5141"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12665"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"88304"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"4"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"96"},{"type":"tags","id":"1051"},{"type":"tags","id":"1052"},{"type":"tags","id":"1122"},{"type":"tags","id":"2942"},{"type":"tags","id":"4578"},{"type":"tags","id":"5771"},{"type":"tags","id":"12909"},{"type":"tags","id":"12919"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"8641"},{"type":"contributions","id":"8898"},{"type":"contributions","id":"10479"},{"type":"contributions","id":"11239"},{"type":"contributions","id":"11746"},{"type":"contributions","id":"14962"},{"type":"contributions","id":"15299"},{"type":"contributions","id":"15902"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"105835","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/105835"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 33-year-old woman presents to the Emergency Department with abdominal pain, nausea and vomiting. She is mildly confused. She has a medical history of type 1 diabetes.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination her pulse rate is 115/min, blood pressure 105/65 mmHg, respiratory rate 28/min, SpO\u003Csub\u003E2\u003C/sub\u003E 97%, on room air and temperature 36.7\u003Csup\u003Eo\u003C/sup\u003EC. She has a fruity smell to her breath and a deep, rapid breathing pattern. She weighs 59 kg.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EInvestigations show a random blood sugar of 19.7 mmol/L (6.0-10.0) and ketones: +++ on urine dipstick. Her serum creatinine is 70 mmol/L (45-90), sodium 140 mmol/L (135-145) and potassium 5.6 mmol/L (3.5-5.0). An arterial blood gas analysis shows:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EpH: 7.02 (7.35 - 7.45)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EpCO2: 22 mmHg (35-45)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHCO3: 8 mmol/L (22-28)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIntravenous (IV) fluids and an insulin infusion are commenced.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following IV fluid regimens would be the most appropriate initially?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["0.9% saline at 1L/hr","0.45% saline at 1L/ hr with potassium 20mmol over 2 hours","100 ml bolus of 3% hypertonic saline in 10-15 minutes","0.9% saline with 10% dextrose at 125ml/hr","0.9% saline at 1L/hour with with potassium 20mmol over 2 hours"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EDiabetic ketoacidosis (DKA) is a severe complication in individuals with type 1 diabetes. It results from a deficiency of insulin, leading to hyperglycaemia, ketosis, and metabolic acidosis. In DKA, the body starts breaking down fat for energy, releasing ketones and causing the blood to become acidic. Symptoms include abdominal pain, nausea, vomiting, confusion, deep and rapid breathing, and a fruity smell in the breath. Immediate management involves fluid resuscitation with isotonic saline (0.9%) to correct dehydration and restore intravascular volume. Concurrently, insulin therapy is initiated to address hyperglycemia and suppress ketone production.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003E0.9% saline at 1L/hr \u003C/strong\u003Eis the most appropriate in this clinical scenario. In DKA, patients often present with dehydration due to osmotic diuresis caused by hyperglycaemia. Therefore, 0.9% saline is crucial for volume resuscitation to restore intravascular volume and improve tissue perfusion. This option is relevant in conditions of hypovolaemia, such as dehydration due to severe vomiting, diarrhea, or inadequate fluid intake.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003E0.45% saline at 1L/hr with potassium 20mmol over 2 hours: \u003C/strong\u003EHypotonic saline is relevant in conditions where there is hypernatraemia or where serum osmolality needs gradual reduction, such as in the management of hyperosmolar hyperglycaemic state (HHS). Unlike DKA, patients with HHS may present with extreme hyperglycaemia and less pronounced ketosis. In such cases, the gradual reduction in serum osmolality with hypotonic saline can help prevent rapid shifts of water into the brain cells, minimising the risk of cerebral oedema. In the clinical stem, the patient has a normal sodium, and the potassium is more than 5.5, thus neither hypotonic saline nor potassium replacement are indicated.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003E100 ml bolus of 3% hypertonic saline in 10-15 minutes: \u003C/strong\u003EHypertonic saline does not have a role in this patient presenting with diabetic ketoacidosis. It is typically used in cases of acute, symptomatic and severe hyponatraemia.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003E0.9% saline with 10% dextrose at 125ml/hr: \u003C/strong\u003EThis option is relevant in the management of hypoglycaemia or to prevent hypoglycaemia in patients receiving insulin therapy, when the glucose level is less than\u00a015mmol/L. Given that the patient\u0027s blood sugar is 19.7mmol/L, this option is incorrect. However, the patient is likely to transition to a 5% glucose IV infusion (125ml/hour) once her BSL is less than 15mmol/L.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003E0.9% saline 1L/hour with potassium 20mmol over 2 hours: \u003C/strong\u003EPatients with DKA often have total body potassium deficits despite elevated serum potassium levels due to intracellular shifts. Providing potassium supplementation in the IV fluid helps prevent hypokalaemia as insulin therapy drives potassium back into cells. Patients with plasma potassium more than 5.5 mmol/L\u00a0do not require supplementation, patients with plasma potassium between 3.5-5.5 mmol/L require replacement at\u00a020 mmol/L of K+ infusion in 1L 0.9% 0.9% sodium chloride over 2 hours. If the potassium value is \u0026lt;3.5 senior review and ICU admission is required for a higher rate of potassium infusion.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["In DKA, optimal resuscitation is with isotonic saline (0.9%) 1L/hr in a normotensive patient"],"references":["Lizzo JM, Goyal A, Gupta V. Adult Diabetic Ketoacidosis. [Updated 2022 Jul 12]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2023 Jan.","Management of diabetic ketoacidosis and hyperosmolar hyperglycaemic state in adults in the emergency department [Internet]. 2021 April. Available from: https://aci.health.nsw.gov.au/networks/eci/clinical/clinical-tools/endocrine/diabetic-ketoacidosis-dka-hyperosmolar-hyperglycaemic-state-hhs."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"88304"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12665"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"88304","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/88304"},"attributes":{"creat